00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:03.880
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yes, Steve.

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:05.296
STEVEN COOK: So
this is originally

00:04:05.296 --> 00:04:06.660
from North Africa, right?

00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:07.040
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yes.

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:09.570
STEVEN COOK: But basically,
almost every Israeli restaurant

00:04:09.570 --> 00:04:11.445
you walk into, you'll
find this on the table.

00:04:11.445 --> 00:04:14.370
So how does something that's
from one part of the world

00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:19.754
become part of the food
cuisine of an entire country?

00:04:19.754 --> 00:04:22.170
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Well, I
mean, I think that's the thing,

00:04:22.170 --> 00:04:25.135
because Israel is, at
one point, super young.

00:04:25.135 --> 00:04:26.010
It's seven years old.

00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:33.420
But also the culture of Israel,
or the diaspora, that thousands

00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:36.150
of years have sort of brought
back all their cooking

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:37.380
traditions.

00:04:37.380 --> 00:04:41.070
And the gastronomy is to
one tiny little place,

00:04:41.070 --> 00:04:42.930
everything is this
sort of mishmash.

00:04:42.930 --> 00:04:47.110
And you see it in
very quick, real time.

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:48.720
I moved back to Israel.

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:50.819
I was born there, but I
moved back in the '80s,

00:04:50.819 --> 00:04:52.860
and there was a huge wave
of Ethiopian immigrants

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:55.140
that nobody knew
about up until then.

00:04:55.140 --> 00:04:56.880
It was the sort of
like a lost tribe.

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:01.540
They came back and now there's
heavy use of fenugreek, teff.

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:05.530
And Ethiopian cuisine is
part of the conversation now.

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:08.950
So in the '50s, the
Moroccans, the Libyans,

00:05:08.950 --> 00:05:10.480
and the Algerians--

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:12.220
not yet the
Tunisians, I believe--

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:13.240
moved back.

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:17.312
They brought with them matbucha,
which is served, like I said,

00:05:17.312 --> 00:05:19.270
it could be a condiment,
it could be breakfast,

00:05:19.270 --> 00:05:21.880
it could be anything.

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:24.600
Basically, every
kebab shop in Israel

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:27.970
serves this as like,
"ketchup" or salsa.

00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:31.630
And, now, also when you sit
down in a restaurant in Israel

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:33.550
and you're presented
with a spicy condiment,

00:05:33.550 --> 00:05:37.480
it used to be harissa, but
the Yemenite Jews brought back

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:39.380
zhug, which is also part of it.

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:47.990
So it's impossible to avoid this
tapestry of culture in Israel.

00:05:47.990 --> 00:05:49.760
It just happens.

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:52.430
It just happens
sort of organically.

00:05:52.430 --> 00:05:52.930
Yeah?

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:54.295
Did that answer your question.

