00:06:11.870 --> 00:06:12.900
And then you let it go.

00:06:12.900 --> 00:06:13.900
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:06:13.900 --> 00:06:15.220
You'll let it go on a
very low temperature

00:06:15.220 --> 00:06:16.310
for a very long time.

00:06:16.310 --> 00:06:19.780
And actually, what I'll do
is put my oven at a very low

00:06:19.780 --> 00:06:21.550
temperature, like 200 degrees.

00:06:21.550 --> 00:06:23.260
I'll start it at night
and then I'll just

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:27.070
put it in a cast iron,
or something like that,

00:06:27.070 --> 00:06:28.090
very lightly covered.

00:06:28.090 --> 00:06:30.250
And just rock it out
overnight, and when

00:06:30.250 --> 00:06:33.490
you wake up in the morning,
you're like, is that coffee?

00:06:33.490 --> 00:06:34.900
Is that my matbucha?

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:36.460
I don't know.

00:06:36.460 --> 00:06:39.760
Also, if you've noticed, I've
been adding salt in layers.

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:42.910
I don't like just adding
all my seasoning at the end.

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:44.020
I like to add.

00:06:44.020 --> 00:06:47.440
Whenever you add a new
component to this pot,

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:50.260
I want it to taste
excellent by itself.

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:52.510
That's kind of the rule,
I think, with braising

00:06:52.510 --> 00:06:59.500
or with complex saucing
or sauce cooking,

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:02.485
is every time you add a new
aromatic or another component,

00:07:02.485 --> 00:07:04.360
you want to treat it as
though you were going

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:05.890
to eat this thing by yourself.

00:07:05.890 --> 00:07:07.840
So I always add a
little bit of salt.

00:07:07.840 --> 00:07:10.060
If you're big fans
of spicy, or if you

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:13.430
like coriander or paprika,
also add it in layers.

00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:15.340
The onions and the
peppers get seasoned.

00:07:15.340 --> 00:07:16.870
Tomatoes get seasoned.

00:07:16.870 --> 00:07:18.940
Cook it down and then
you finish at the end.

00:07:18.940 --> 00:07:23.470
That way, the flavor's developed
and it's not just one note.

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:28.030
Also, we're going to get started
with our zucchini schnitzel.

00:07:28.030 --> 00:07:30.890
Have you guys all
had schnitzel before?

00:07:30.890 --> 00:07:32.950
Steve, can you
tell them something

00:07:32.950 --> 00:07:34.680
anecdotal about
schnitzel in Israel?

00:07:34.680 --> 00:07:35.471
STEVEN COOK: I can.

00:07:35.471 --> 00:07:36.790
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Please.

00:07:36.790 --> 00:07:37.210
STEVEN COOK: I can.

00:07:37.210 --> 00:07:39.001
I mean, when Jews first
started coming back

00:07:39.001 --> 00:07:41.120
to Israel around the
turn of the 19th century,

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:43.480
it was primarily German
Jews at that time, that wave

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:46.390
of immigration, so that
schnitzel was a dish that they

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:48.340
brought over to Israel.

00:07:48.340 --> 00:07:52.090
They very used to veal, which
wasn't really available when

00:07:52.090 --> 00:07:54.790
they got to Palestine.

00:07:54.790 --> 00:07:56.920
And so chickens were a
lot cheaper and a lot more

00:07:56.920 --> 00:07:58.840
widely available, so
chicken schnitzel sort of

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:03.370
became the unofficial
tourist food of Israel.

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:06.580
Many of us encountered it for
the first time on a tour bus

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:08.350
and it wasn't very good.

00:08:08.350 --> 00:08:10.090
And it's gotten a bad
rap over the years,

00:08:10.090 --> 00:08:13.510
but it's kind of
making a comeback.

00:08:13.510 --> 00:08:16.000
I mean, it's basically
fried chicken,

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.570
so it's inherently good.

00:08:18.570 --> 00:08:21.465
But it became really
popular in Israel

00:08:21.465 --> 00:08:22.840
in the early days
of the country,

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:26.119
because it was a super poor
country that was very isolated,

00:08:26.119 --> 00:08:27.160
from a trade perspective.

00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:29.080
People didn't have
ovens their home,

00:08:29.080 --> 00:08:32.049
so they'd take a pounded out
piece of chicken and bread it

00:08:32.049 --> 00:08:33.070
and fry it in a pan.

00:08:33.070 --> 00:08:34.386
It was cheap.

00:08:34.386 --> 00:08:36.010
It looked like a lot
of food because it

00:08:36.010 --> 00:08:37.600
was pounded out really thin.

00:08:37.600 --> 00:08:41.419
And it was something that
they actually used to teach.

00:08:41.419 --> 00:08:44.290
As each successive wave of
immigrants came to Israel,

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:46.330
they actually would
have cooking classes

00:08:46.330 --> 00:08:48.079
and teach everybody
how to make schnitzel.

00:08:48.079 --> 00:08:51.430
So something that started
out as European and German

00:08:51.430 --> 00:08:53.430
became widely, widely
adopted in the country.

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:58.880
And you encounter it in museum
cafeterias and tour groups.

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:01.462
And then there is an
awesome place right

00:09:01.462 --> 00:09:02.920
on the beach in
Tel Aviv that makes

00:09:02.920 --> 00:09:05.710
these incredible schnitzel
sandwiches that, I don't know,

00:09:05.710 --> 00:09:07.870
taste so good after you
come out of the water.

00:09:07.870 --> 00:09:08.530
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:10.210
And also, you can eat
them like, standing up

00:09:10.210 --> 00:09:12.043
in your bathing suit
with no shirt on, which

00:09:12.043 --> 00:09:14.050
is a pretty amazing thing.

00:09:14.050 --> 00:09:18.340
But also, it's sort of
become this iconic dish

00:09:18.340 --> 00:09:21.100
because everybody that's
ever visited Israel usually

00:09:21.100 --> 00:09:22.960
ends up eating schnitzel.

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:24.630
And it's become almost highbrow.

00:09:24.630 --> 00:09:27.324
Now, hipsters have
started making schnitzels.

00:09:27.324 --> 00:09:29.740
What do they call them, like
schnitzel arias, or something

00:09:29.740 --> 00:09:30.290
like that.

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:32.770
And all they make are
these schnitzel sandwiches

00:09:32.770 --> 00:09:34.660
either in pita or in baguettes.

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:37.210
And they use the zhug,
the [? harees, ?]

00:09:37.210 --> 00:09:40.330
all these different
condiments to make what are,

00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:42.445
essentially, fried
chicken sandwiches.

00:09:42.445 --> 00:09:44.110
STEVEN COOK: Yeah.

00:09:44.110 --> 00:09:46.600
SPEAKER: So what led you
to zucchini schnitzel?

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:51.760
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I just feel
