00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:02.770
And I feel like you need
something kind of exciting,

00:10:02.770 --> 00:10:04.750
and it's sort of a star.

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:07.010
If you treat it like
a piece of protein,

00:10:07.010 --> 00:10:09.630
it's something really
special, and nobody's also

00:10:09.630 --> 00:10:10.380
really doing it.

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:15.660
I mean, people do eggplant like
this, sort of like Milanese.

00:10:15.660 --> 00:10:19.140
So what is cool about this is
we're adding a Yemenite soup

00:10:19.140 --> 00:10:21.330
spice mix called [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:23.640
And it's like turmeric,
cumin, and black pepper.

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:30.810
And what we're also doing
is using beaten eggs to,

00:10:30.810 --> 00:10:33.570
obviously, adhere the
motza meal to crust it.

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:36.990
But it acts as a brine or a
marinade, which is awesome

00:10:36.990 --> 00:10:40.470
because normally, when we grew
up going to culinary school,

00:10:40.470 --> 00:10:43.530
European chefs would say,
you don't ever do this.

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:45.270
Because you don't
add salt. You don't

00:10:45.270 --> 00:10:47.370
let things sit in an
egg wash for too long.

00:10:47.370 --> 00:10:50.010
And the beautiful thing
about this cuisine

00:10:50.010 --> 00:10:52.140
is that it
contradicts everything

00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:54.090
that my culinary school
teachers taught me.

00:10:54.090 --> 00:10:56.350
And it's usually grandmothers
that are doing it,

00:10:56.350 --> 00:10:57.934
which I love.

00:10:57.934 --> 00:10:59.850
STEVEN COOK: So you're
not flowering it first.

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:00.720
You're going right into the egg?

00:11:00.720 --> 00:11:01.500
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I'm
going right in there,

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:02.760
and that's the other thing.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:05.599
I'm glad that you
brought that up, Steve.

00:11:05.599 --> 00:11:07.140
STEVEN COOK: Yeah,
I was almost going

00:11:07.140 --> 00:11:08.644
to stop you because
I also thought

00:11:08.644 --> 00:11:09.810
that's not the way to do it.

00:11:09.810 --> 00:11:10.040
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:11.610
Yeah, so that's the thing.

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:15.060
If you guys have ever
made any sort of Milanese.

00:11:15.060 --> 00:11:16.890
It's like flour, egg
wash, breadcrumbs.

00:11:16.890 --> 00:11:19.260
That's the standard
thing that we're taught.

00:11:19.260 --> 00:11:22.290
Flour doesn't actually
need to be there.

00:11:22.290 --> 00:11:24.780
This will adhere really
nicely, and you'll

00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:26.525
get something really
nice and crisp.

00:11:26.525 --> 00:11:28.650
The worst part about cutting
into something breaded

00:11:28.650 --> 00:11:31.350
is when you slice it and
all the breading falls off.

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:33.440
And you're like,
all right, well, I

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:34.790
guess I need a sharper knife.

00:11:34.790 --> 00:11:38.280
No, don't listen to the
European pastry chefs that

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:39.990
taught you how to cook food.

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:42.180
You just simply batter
it and marinate it,

00:11:42.180 --> 00:11:45.010
and then we're going to bread
it in motza meal and fry it.

00:11:45.010 --> 00:11:47.610
And this works really
well with chicken.

00:11:47.610 --> 00:11:48.930
This works well with veal.

00:11:48.930 --> 00:11:50.670
This works well with eggplant.

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:52.860
This works well
with green tomatoes.

00:11:52.860 --> 00:11:55.320
And it's super simple.

00:11:55.320 --> 00:11:58.710
I'm using this amazing-- do you
guys want to pass that around?

00:11:58.710 --> 00:11:59.940
It's so good.

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:03.810
You usually add it to chicken
soup or veal shank soup.

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:06.810
You can add, really,
whatever spice blend you want

00:12:06.810 --> 00:12:10.260
and it will act as a
brine and really permeate

00:12:10.260 --> 00:12:11.350
the zucchini or the meat.

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:13.224
STEVEN COOK: But don't
get it on your fingers

00:12:13.224 --> 00:12:14.855
because it will stain,
or your clothes.

00:12:14.855 --> 00:12:17.230
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah, if
you're wearing a white shirt.

00:12:17.230 --> 00:12:18.229
STEVEN COOK: Be careful.

00:12:18.229 --> 00:12:20.490
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
It'll be festive.

00:12:20.490 --> 00:12:22.620
So Steve, you want to
show them your hummus?

00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:23.370
STEVEN COOK: Yeah.

00:12:23.370 --> 00:12:27.630
So we have a recipe for hummus
in our first cookbook, which

00:12:27.630 --> 00:12:30.030
is really based on what we
do with the restaurants.

00:12:30.030 --> 00:12:32.347
And it's super easy but
it requires a little bit

00:12:32.347 --> 00:12:33.180
of advance planning.

00:12:33.180 --> 00:12:34.690
You have to soak the
chickpeas overnight.

00:12:34.690 --> 00:12:36.090
You have to cook the chickpeas.

00:12:36.090 --> 00:12:38.700
So we really wanted to
come up with a little bit

00:12:38.700 --> 00:12:41.820
of a shortcut, because we feel
like there's really no reason

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:44.729
to buy hummus from
the grocery store

00:12:44.729 --> 00:12:46.770
because you can make
something that's super cheap

00:12:46.770 --> 00:12:50.280
and you can make
it really quickly.

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:53.040
The idea came to us-- we
were doing our six minute

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:57.180
abs one day and we were like, we
could do hummus in five minutes

00:12:57.180 --> 00:12:58.920
and we would be rich.

00:12:58.920 --> 00:13:02.850
So we're going to do it
all in the food processor.

00:13:02.850 --> 00:13:04.940
When we're done,
for the most part,

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:07.410
this is the only thing
you have to clean.

00:13:07.410 --> 00:13:10.140
And it was really based on--

00:13:10.140 --> 00:13:12.690
so the great folks at
Google have actually

00:13:12.690 --> 00:13:15.420
done the dirty work of
taking tahini out of a jar

00:13:15.420 --> 00:13:17.400
and emulsifying it in this bowl.

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:19.890
But if you've ever
opened a jar of tahini,

00:13:19.890 --> 00:13:22.170
or natural peanut butter,
or anything like that,

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:23.617
you know that
there's oil on top.

00:13:23.617 --> 00:13:25.450
There's like, some nice
stuff in the middle,

00:13:25.450 --> 00:13:27.570
and then a bit of
sludge on the bottom.

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:31.440
And a lot of hummus recipes
will call for like, let's say,

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:32.760
six ounces of that.

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:34.950
So you have to get
in there, mix it up,

00:13:34.950 --> 00:13:39.690
and then you're left with
like nine ounces of stuff

00:13:39.690 --> 00:13:42.430
that maybe you'll use, or maybe
it'll just sit there forever.

00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:45.144
And it makes a mess, and
this is not water soluble,

00:13:45.144 --> 00:13:47.060
so cleaning up after
this is really difficult.

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:48.880
So we tried to build the recipe.

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:50.520
This is literally one--

00:13:50.520 --> 00:13:52.770
I think it's a 14
ounce jar of tahini

00:13:52.770 --> 00:13:56.205
that you can literally just
dump the whole thing in.

00:13:56.205 --> 00:13:57.720
You don't have to mix it up.

00:13:57.720 --> 00:13:59.942
Just dump it in and
recycle the jar.

00:13:59.942 --> 00:14:01.650
SPEAKER: I'm sold on
this recipe already.

00:14:01.650 --> 00:14:03.483
STEVEN COOK: So this
is all the ingredients.

00:14:03.483 --> 00:14:06.030
We're going to start,
counterintuitively--

00:14:06.030 --> 00:14:09.330
Israeli and Palestinian
stock almost is really not

00:14:09.330 --> 00:14:11.700
super big on garlic and lemon.

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:13.420
It's really mostly
about the tahini.

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:14.836
So we're just going
to, literally,

00:14:14.836 --> 00:14:18.782
put a couple of small
slices of garlic.

00:14:18.782 --> 00:14:20.990
The thing with raw garlic
is it kind of will radiate.

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:25.216
It will continue to
radiate through the dish.

00:14:25.216 --> 00:14:27.090
And then it calls for
the juice of one lemon.

00:14:27.090 --> 00:14:30.210
These are a little bit small
so I'll probably use 1 and 1/2.

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:32.580
And I like to put the lemon
right on top of the garlic

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:34.380
because it can kind of
mellow it out a little bit

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:36.171
and keep it from being--
it almost cooks it

00:14:36.171 --> 00:14:40.140
a little bit, keeps it from
being super aggressive.

00:14:45.350 --> 00:14:46.350
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:14:46.350 --> 00:14:47.790
There's nothing worse
than eating hummus

00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:49.290
and then two days
later you're like,

00:14:49.290 --> 00:14:53.229
I don't know why I still
have that taste in my mouth.

00:14:53.229 --> 00:14:55.020
STEVEN COOK: And then
the only other things

00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:57.000
we're really going to
add, besides the tahini

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
and the chickpeas, is
a little bit of cumin

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:06.150
and a little bit of salt.
And the other nice thing

00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:09.300
is we're using canned
chickpeas, which a lot of people

00:15:09.300 --> 00:15:15.390
might say is an inferior
product to dried,

00:15:15.390 --> 00:15:16.890
soaked, cooked chickpeas.

00:15:16.890 --> 00:15:19.777
But we actually
feel the opposite,

00:15:19.777 --> 00:15:22.110
because when you buy dried
chickpeas in a grocery store,

00:15:22.110 --> 00:15:23.901
they could have been
sitting in a warehouse

00:15:23.901 --> 00:15:25.590
somewhere for two
years or two months.

00:15:25.590 --> 00:15:27.660
And you got to cook
them and they could take

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:29.490
45 minutes or eight hours or--

00:15:29.490 --> 00:15:29.780
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Whenever.

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:30.790
STEVEN COOK: --every
once in a while.

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:31.300
Right.

00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:33.425
Every once in a while, you
get a batch of chickpeas

00:15:33.425 --> 00:15:36.120
that literally never cooks.

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:42.330
So just adding some cumin
and some salt. And then

00:15:42.330 --> 00:15:45.001
we're going to put the
whole bowl of this in.

00:15:48.339 --> 00:15:50.880
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: You guys can
see this matbucha cooking out

00:15:50.880 --> 00:15:51.380
right now.

00:15:51.380 --> 00:15:54.450
It sort of resembles
a tomato sauce.

00:15:54.450 --> 00:15:57.130
And honestly, this with
ziti would be fantastic.

00:15:57.130 --> 00:16:00.420
But we're going to let this
cook it down and down and down.

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:03.390
We're going to add a little
bit of olive oil to it

00:16:03.390 --> 00:16:05.972
and really let the flavors
concentrate and bind.

00:16:05.972 --> 00:16:08.430
STEVEN COOK: All right so we're
going to just buzz this up.

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:19.040
So the secret, or the key,
to the hummus that we make

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:23.060
is we like to make a really
super light and whipped tahini

00:16:23.060 --> 00:16:24.931
sauce as the base.

00:16:24.931 --> 00:16:26.930
The last thing we're going
out is the chickpeas.

00:16:26.930 --> 00:16:28.430
So when you get
to that final step

00:16:28.430 --> 00:16:29.930
before you add the
chickpeas, you're

00:16:29.930 --> 00:16:32.390
going to have a beautiful,
well-seasoned sauce that

00:16:32.390 --> 00:16:35.900
goes with anything from
zucchini schnitzel to fish

00:16:35.900 --> 00:16:36.980
to roasted meat.

00:16:36.980 --> 00:16:37.880
It's super versatile.

00:16:37.880 --> 00:16:42.106
We use it at the restaurant
for almost everything.

00:16:42.106 --> 00:16:44.480
But in order to get it whipped,
we're going to add water.

00:16:44.480 --> 00:16:47.900
And the thing about
tahini is it's mostly fat.

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:50.670
And when you mix fat and water,
sometimes it's problematic.

00:16:50.670 --> 00:16:53.347
So the trick is
to use ice water,

00:16:53.347 --> 00:16:55.680
and I'm going to show you,
when you first add the water,

00:16:55.680 --> 00:16:59.910
it's going to look
really gross and broken.

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:01.470
SPEAKER: A technical
term, gross.

00:17:01.470 --> 00:17:03.470
STEVEN COOK: I don't know,
