and then it's done.

00:22:20.400 --> 00:22:22.460
Stop a little bit and
make sure you scrape down

00:22:22.460 --> 00:22:23.960
the sides once or twice.

00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:26.060
SPEAKER: The color is beautiful.

00:22:26.060 --> 00:22:27.726
STEVEN COOK: Yeah,
it's really gorgeous.

00:22:30.730 --> 00:22:32.262
AUDIENCE: You're not singing.

00:22:32.262 --> 00:22:33.470
STEVEN COOK: In my head I am.

00:22:33.470 --> 00:22:35.570
SPEAKER: It's
internal monologue.

00:22:46.449 --> 00:22:47.990
STEVEN COOK: The
only real difference

00:22:47.990 --> 00:22:50.844
with using canned chickpeas
is that they cook--

00:22:50.844 --> 00:22:53.260
I mean, they do a beautiful
job of cooking them in the can

00:22:53.260 --> 00:22:55.850
so that each chickpea
maintains integrity

00:22:55.850 --> 00:22:58.040
and it's got a little
bit of bite left to it.

00:22:58.040 --> 00:23:00.755
When we cook chickpeas from
dry at the restaurants,

00:23:00.755 --> 00:23:02.630
by the time that we're
finished cooking them,

00:23:02.630 --> 00:23:04.550
they're not recognizable
as chickpeas.

00:23:04.550 --> 00:23:06.950
They're just mush, and
that's what contributes

00:23:06.950 --> 00:23:09.140
to like a super creamy texture.

00:23:09.140 --> 00:23:11.690
But that texture,
really, is just a matter

00:23:11.690 --> 00:23:13.400
of personal preference.

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:15.604
This is going to be
still very, very smooth,

00:23:15.604 --> 00:23:17.520
but you'll have a little
bit of texture in it.

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:23.330
SPEAKER: Yeah, question?

00:23:23.330 --> 00:23:32.691
AUDIENCE: How much [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:32.691 --> 00:23:34.690
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: That's
a really good question

00:23:34.690 --> 00:23:35.680
and I'll repeat it.

00:23:35.680 --> 00:23:36.190
SPEAKER: Paraphrase it.

00:23:36.190 --> 00:23:36.730
Yes, thank you.

00:23:36.730 --> 00:23:38.105
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Yeah, so it's,

00:23:38.105 --> 00:23:41.170
how much of Israeli
cuisine is kosher?

00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:50.890
So culturally, the
laws of kosher--

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:54.340
the way that the food came
back from the diaspora

00:23:54.340 --> 00:23:56.650
came mostly through Jews.

00:23:56.650 --> 00:24:02.140
So Yemenite cuisine,
North African cuisine.

00:24:02.140 --> 00:24:06.696
My family's from Bulgaria,
but from Spain, originally.

00:24:06.696 --> 00:24:08.070
And so the food
that they brought

00:24:08.070 --> 00:24:10.690
about wasn't Spanish and
wasn't totally Ottoman,

00:24:10.690 --> 00:24:13.760
because the Ottomans had also
conquered the Balkans for oil.

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:18.220
It was still laws of
kosher were maintained.

00:24:18.220 --> 00:24:22.000
So it's not just
Yemenite food from Yemen.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:25.240
It's Yemen without
milk and meat together,

00:24:25.240 --> 00:24:28.595
with the cooking
on Shabbat, which

00:24:28.595 --> 00:24:30.220
is a big thing, that
overnight cooking.

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:34.150
Because you're not allowed,
from sundown till sunset--

00:24:34.150 --> 00:24:36.250
sundown on Friday till
sunset on Saturday,

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:38.110
you're not allowed to
mess with your ovens.

00:24:38.110 --> 00:24:39.818
And you're also kind
of commanded to have

00:24:39.818 --> 00:24:43.044
an extravagant meal on Saturday,
which is a huge problem

00:24:43.044 --> 00:24:44.710
because you can't
turn ovens on and off.

00:24:44.710 --> 00:24:47.860
So everybody's got their
own version of cassoulet,

00:24:47.860 --> 00:24:50.350
or overnight Sabbath stew.

00:24:50.350 --> 00:24:54.610
So I would say, as I was saying
before, we're not kosher,

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:57.400
but we wanted to keep
it a little bit real

00:24:57.400 --> 00:25:00.130
because the laws of Kashrut
are relevant when it comes

00:25:00.130 --> 00:25:02.440
to eating, like the
cultural way that you

00:25:02.440 --> 00:25:07.250
eat in Israel for the
majority of the population.

00:25:07.250 --> 00:25:10.780
So I'm not sure, actually.

00:25:10.780 --> 00:25:13.080
I almost forgot the
intent of that question,

00:25:13.080 --> 00:25:15.110
but I hope I
answered part of it.

00:25:15.110 --> 00:25:17.080
But that's a good way
for us to distinguish.

00:25:17.080 --> 00:25:22.300
When we started, we we're
like, well, if we're not kosher

00:25:22.300 --> 00:25:25.570
and we're roasting lamb, I
want to serve it with yogurt.

00:25:25.570 --> 00:25:27.370
But once I start
serving with yogurt,

00:25:27.370 --> 00:25:31.600
that takes away a little
bit from like the intent

00:25:31.600 --> 00:25:33.260
that we want our
customers to have,

00:25:33.260 --> 00:25:37.910
that we wanted to cook with,
to understand that how it was.

00:25:37.910 --> 00:25:40.330
So that the laws of Kashrut,
even though we're not

00:25:40.330 --> 00:25:43.130
kosher restaurant, the
way that you cook really,

00:25:43.130 --> 00:25:44.920
really matters.

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:48.640
There's a Yemenite bread called
kubaneh, which literally, it's

00:25:48.640 --> 00:25:53.500
a yeasted bread that goes in a
200 degree oven for 12 hours.

00:25:53.500 --> 00:25:55.750
And you eat it Saturday
morning with hard boiled eggs,

00:25:55.750 --> 00:25:58.134
and it's like delicious.

00:25:58.134 --> 00:26:00.050
Not the lightest thing
in the world, but very,

00:26:00.050 --> 00:26:01.240
very, very good.

00:26:01.240 --> 00:26:03.610
And having that Saturday
morning experience

00:26:03.610 --> 00:26:05.710
is something that is
very relevant to the way

00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:07.630
that we cook.

00:26:07.630 --> 00:26:11.500
Also, cassoulet, too,
came from hameen,

00:26:11.500 --> 00:26:13.800
or from [INAUDIBLE] which is--

00:26:13.800 --> 00:26:17.459
the Ashkenazi Jews made
[INAUDIBLE] and the Moroccan

00:26:17.459 --> 00:26:19.000
Jews made hameen,
and usually, that's

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:23.590
a legume meat stew
that goes overnight.

00:26:23.590 --> 00:26:24.448
SPEAKER: Yeah?

00:26:24.448 --> 00:26:30.821
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:30.821 --> 00:26:32.070
STEVEN COOK: We've tried that.

00:26:32.070 --> 00:26:35.920
It doesn't quite-- it
gets a little bit softer,

00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:37.286
but it doesn't quite--

00:26:37.286 --> 00:26:38.910
I think once they're
cooked and cooled,

00:26:38.910 --> 00:26:40.580
it's kind of hard to
take them further along.

00:26:40.580 --> 00:26:42.705
We found that hasn't been
really worth the trouble.

00:26:45.459 --> 00:26:46.500
SPEAKER: Yeah, finish up.

00:26:46.500 --> 00:26:47.320
STEVEN COOK: I'm going
to plate this up.

00:26:47.320 --> 00:26:49.230
So I mean, the only
clean up we really

00:26:49.230 --> 00:26:52.770
have is this, a spatula,
a couple of bowls.

00:26:52.770 --> 00:26:54.590
But it's pretty clean.

00:26:54.590 --> 00:26:56.340
Actually, I want to
buzz it one more time.

00:26:56.340 --> 00:27:01.630
I just season it with
a little extra squeeze

00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:03.300
of lemon and some salt.

00:27:03.300 --> 00:27:06.210
And the plating of this
is actually important.

00:27:06.210 --> 00:27:09.390
When Israelis invite
you to go eat hummus,

00:27:09.390 --> 00:27:12.300
they ask you, literally, do you
want to go wipe some hummus?

00:27:12.300 --> 00:27:14.120
Because it's the
action of dragging

00:27:14.120 --> 00:27:16.050
the pita through the hummus.

00:27:16.050 --> 00:27:17.730
And so the way
that you plate it,

00:27:17.730 --> 00:27:21.510
traditionally, is both
beautiful and also functional.

00:27:21.510 --> 00:27:23.280
So I will demonstrate that now.

00:27:30.405 --> 00:27:32.630
So you want to put the
hummus in the middle.

00:27:32.630 --> 00:27:35.000
You want to take the back
of the spoon and go around

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:38.150
and sort of run the hummus
up on the rim of the bowl,

00:27:38.150 --> 00:27:39.337
kind of like a wave.

00:27:39.337 --> 00:27:40.670
It just kind of makes it easier.

00:27:40.670 --> 00:27:42.253
And a shallow bowl
is great because it

00:27:42.253 --> 00:27:44.240
makes it easier to
get in there and not

00:27:44.240 --> 00:27:46.880
get hummus on your sleeve.

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:51.880
And then we have, in the book,
about 25 different toppings

00:27:51.880 --> 00:27:54.350
of hummus, which are not
super traditional in Israel,

00:27:54.350 --> 00:27:56.780
but it's such a great
campus, because it's rich

00:27:56.780 --> 00:27:58.470
but it's also kind of neutral.

00:27:58.470 --> 00:28:01.610
So we top it from everything
from pine nut and broccoli

00:28:01.610 --> 00:28:07.580
pesto to ground lamb with
[? faharad ?] and pine nuts.

00:28:07.580 --> 00:28:09.440
It kind of goes with everything.

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:11.600
But the simplest
way to do it is just

00:28:11.600 --> 00:28:22.382
a little bit of olive
oil, some chopped parsley,

00:28:22.382 --> 00:28:23.090
and some paprika.

00:28:26.120 --> 00:28:27.940
SPEAKER: Beautiful, absolutely.

00:28:27.940 --> 00:28:30.770
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
It's good for wiping.

00:28:30.770 --> 00:28:32.270
I'm going to finish
this up as well.

00:28:32.270 --> 00:28:34.910
We're just going to take
some of our matbucha,

00:28:34.910 --> 00:28:40.871
spoon it down with a
little bit of hummus,

00:28:40.871 --> 00:28:52.090
the zucchini, some cilantro.

00:29:02.303 --> 00:29:05.090
I feel like finishing everything
with excessive amounts

00:29:05.090 --> 00:29:06.990
of olive oil is the way to do.

00:29:12.170 --> 00:29:14.200
There it is.

00:29:14.200 --> 00:29:16.960
SPEAKER: Beautiful.

