00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:44.060
but I have one for you first.

00:29:44.060 --> 00:29:46.760
So in addition to Zahav
and your cookbooks,

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:48.390
you guys are the CookNSolo team.

00:29:48.390 --> 00:29:50.330
So how did that come to be?

00:29:52.699 --> 00:29:54.240
STEVEN COOK: How
did that come to be?

00:29:54.240 --> 00:29:57.020
We've been working
together for 13 years now.

00:29:57.020 --> 00:30:01.880
We were introduced, actually, by
my wife, who's from Pittsburgh,

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:03.230
where Mike grew up.

00:30:03.230 --> 00:30:06.720
So they were family
friends, and my wife

00:30:06.720 --> 00:30:09.370
introduced about 13 years ago
because the first restaurant

00:30:09.370 --> 00:30:11.500
ever opened I was
looking for a chef.

00:30:11.500 --> 00:30:16.310
And my wife Cher was like,
you really got to meet Mike.

00:30:16.310 --> 00:30:19.910
He's the other Jewish
line cook in Philadelphia.

00:30:19.910 --> 00:30:22.072
SPEAKER: The two of them.

00:30:22.072 --> 00:30:23.780
STEVEN COOK: We had
apartments in Philly.

00:30:23.780 --> 00:30:25.070
We both moved to
Philly the same year.

00:30:25.070 --> 00:30:27.050
We had apartments
literally right next door

00:30:27.050 --> 00:30:30.184
to each other for a
year and never met.

00:30:30.184 --> 00:30:32.600
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: And I kept
hearing about Steve as well.

00:30:32.600 --> 00:30:34.349
I was working at a
restaurant called Vetri

00:30:34.349 --> 00:30:36.610
and I was going to leave.

00:30:36.610 --> 00:30:39.050
STEVEN COOK: Yeah.

00:30:39.050 --> 00:30:43.889
In retrospect, it was a pretty
hasty, foolish decision.

00:30:43.889 --> 00:30:45.930
We met each other for
coffee for like, 20 minutes

00:30:45.930 --> 00:30:48.080
and then I was like,
you want a job?

00:30:48.080 --> 00:30:49.539
And that's kind of
how it happened.

00:30:49.539 --> 00:30:51.829
SPEAKER: But now it's James
Beard awards and six minute

00:30:51.829 --> 00:30:52.340
abs.

00:30:52.340 --> 00:30:54.470
It clearly worked out.

00:30:54.470 --> 00:30:57.680
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah,
one of those things.

00:30:57.680 --> 00:30:59.460
It's fun, I mean, our business.

00:30:59.460 --> 00:31:01.820
When we started
working together,

00:31:01.820 --> 00:31:03.890
Steve was the owner
of a restaurant that

00:31:03.890 --> 00:31:08.720
had seven employees that
was in 45th and Marchwood,

00:31:08.720 --> 00:31:11.280
past [INAUDIBLE]
campus in West Philly.

00:31:11.280 --> 00:31:12.740
It was this tiny, little BYOB.

00:31:12.740 --> 00:31:17.719
And today, we have 250
employees and 12 restaurants,

00:31:17.719 --> 00:31:18.510
for 13 restaurants?

00:31:18.510 --> 00:31:19.919
12 restaurants.

00:31:19.919 --> 00:31:21.710
SPEAKER: So many that
you're not even sure.

00:31:21.710 --> 00:31:23.465
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Well, that's a lot.

00:31:23.465 --> 00:31:25.850
We try to block it
out, the number, so we

00:31:25.850 --> 00:31:27.950
sleep better at night.

00:31:27.950 --> 00:31:30.230
And yeah, I mean,
we're super different,

00:31:30.230 --> 00:31:33.720
super different people,
and that has really helped.

00:31:33.720 --> 00:31:36.020
But when times are
tough, which they often

00:31:36.020 --> 00:31:38.150
are in restaurants-- it's
like every other day,

00:31:38.150 --> 00:31:40.730
there's some sort
of catastrophe.

00:31:40.730 --> 00:31:44.510
The ability to like bounce
ideas and have support from,

00:31:44.510 --> 00:31:49.380
essentially, your
BFF is very helpful.

00:31:49.380 --> 00:31:50.630
SPEAKER: That's beautiful.

00:31:50.630 --> 00:31:52.130
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
And also auditing

00:31:52.130 --> 00:31:53.960
your terrible decisions,
if it was only us.

00:31:53.960 --> 00:31:57.350
I mean, independently, we come
up with some very bad ideas,

00:31:57.350 --> 00:31:58.977
I think.

00:31:58.977 --> 00:32:01.310
SPEAKER: That's the best
partner, the one who can really

00:32:01.310 --> 00:32:02.615
audit your terrible decisions.

00:32:02.615 --> 00:32:03.740
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Totally.

00:32:03.740 --> 00:32:05.140
SPEAKER: You had a question.

00:32:05.140 --> 00:32:08.269
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so there's
this debate about--

00:32:08.269 --> 00:32:10.060
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
That's a great question,

00:32:10.060 --> 00:32:11.476
and I guess I'll
paraphrase, which

00:32:11.476 --> 00:32:15.080
is what is American
Israeli cuisine's

00:32:15.080 --> 00:32:17.690
role in telling the story,
I guess, of Israeli food?

00:32:17.690 --> 00:32:20.570
I mean, the fact of the matter
is food travels and food

00:32:20.570 --> 00:32:25.130
changes and adopts the
way that people do.

00:32:25.130 --> 00:32:28.230
Now Israeli food in
the US is a big thing.

00:32:28.230 --> 00:32:33.230
And I think that what
we had to do at Zahav

00:32:33.230 --> 00:32:39.620
was break from tradition,
because it wasn't relevant.

00:32:39.620 --> 00:32:42.860
What you have available to you
in Pennsylvania in February

00:32:42.860 --> 00:32:45.080
is, obviously, very
different than the produce

00:32:45.080 --> 00:32:47.360
that you have access
to in the Middle East.

00:32:47.360 --> 00:32:50.090
And it came at a
time where we were

00:32:50.090 --> 00:32:53.510
about to close the
restaurant, we were so slow.

00:32:53.510 --> 00:32:57.260
And I really held on
to this idea of things

00:32:57.260 --> 00:32:58.925
being very traditional.

00:32:58.925 --> 00:33:02.290
At the end of the day,
it doesn't matter.

00:33:02.290 --> 00:33:05.120
My shakshuka, I
think, is very good.

00:33:05.120 --> 00:33:07.190
Regardless of how
good it tastes,

00:33:07.190 --> 00:33:10.250
it's not as good as
the restaurant in Jaffa

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:14.300
that makes it overlooking
the Mediterranean Sea.

00:33:14.300 --> 00:33:16.260
And ordering
tomatoes in February,

00:33:16.260 --> 00:33:19.020
even though they were from
Israel, it doesn't taste right.

00:33:19.020 --> 00:33:20.750
So we had to adapt.

00:33:20.750 --> 00:33:23.480
We had to start pickling
and preserving, using

00:33:23.480 --> 00:33:27.440
spices and techniques
to really tell a story.

00:33:27.440 --> 00:33:31.490
So the visceral reaction
that we got from our guests

00:33:31.490 --> 00:33:32.430
was good enough.

00:33:32.430 --> 00:33:34.730
I didn't need something
to be literal.

00:33:34.730 --> 00:33:36.921
At the end of the
day, my bourekas,

00:33:36.921 --> 00:33:38.420
which were my
grandmother's recipe--

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:43.690
they're this beautiful puff
pastryesque thing that's like

00:33:43.690 --> 00:33:46.010
a turnover that's stuffed
with feta cheese--

00:33:46.010 --> 00:33:49.490
tells the story of my family
going back to the Inquisition

00:33:49.490 --> 00:33:50.754
till now.

00:33:50.754 --> 00:33:52.670
I make it the way that
my grandmother made it.

00:33:52.670 --> 00:33:57.380
It will never taste
as good as hers, ever.

00:33:57.380 --> 00:34:00.170
And when Steve
hired me at Marigold

00:34:00.170 --> 00:34:02.270
and I started taking
her boureka dough

00:34:02.270 --> 00:34:05.180
and stuffing it with
porchinis and foie gras.

00:34:05.180 --> 00:34:06.730
My grandmother would
have hated that.

00:34:06.730 --> 00:34:08.030
She would have thought
it was terrible.

00:34:08.030 --> 00:34:09.155
I thought it was very good.

00:34:09.155 --> 00:34:12.679
But that's the way
that we progressed.

00:34:12.679 --> 00:34:15.020
And I think that that's
probably the big contribution

00:34:15.020 --> 00:34:19.219
is that people are
not only saying--

00:34:19.219 --> 00:34:20.639
it's up to me.

00:34:20.639 --> 00:34:21.620
I'm not a grandparent.

00:34:21.620 --> 00:34:25.560
I need to adapt and change,
and I can take liberties.

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:28.860
But you get to look at a
country from a third person

00:34:28.860 --> 00:34:30.659
point of view, from
a different narrative

00:34:30.659 --> 00:34:35.730
and say, well, the best
Bulgarian restaurant in Jaffa

00:34:35.730 --> 00:34:36.630
is here.

00:34:36.630 --> 00:34:38.460
The best Yemenite
restaurant that I know

00:34:38.460 --> 00:34:40.500
is in Hadera is here.

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:43.440
The best Palestinian restaurant
that I go to is here.

00:34:43.440 --> 00:34:44.909
And we're going to take all--

00:34:44.909 --> 00:34:49.050
I can look at all these
things and pick and choose

00:34:49.050 --> 00:34:53.020
what I want to put on a plate
to tell a different story.

00:34:53.020 --> 00:34:54.270
And I think that's what we do.

00:34:54.270 --> 00:34:56.103
I think if you go to
Israel and ask somebody

00:34:56.103 --> 00:34:57.690
where the best
Israeli restaurant is,

00:34:57.690 --> 00:34:59.140
they have no idea what that is.

00:34:59.140 --> 00:35:01.390
I mean, there's no such thing.

00:35:01.390 --> 00:35:03.660
And so for us to be able to
articulate that, I think,

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:06.320
is important.

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:07.490
SPEAKER: Yeah?

00:35:07.490 --> 00:35:07.910
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Right.

00:35:07.910 --> 00:35:09.743
Where to get good za'tar
and a good baharat?

00:35:09.743 --> 00:35:12.350
I mean, I hate this
answer, which is just like,

00:35:12.350 --> 00:35:13.850
order it online now.

00:35:13.850 --> 00:35:16.190
But when you come
up with cookbooks,

00:35:16.190 --> 00:35:17.240
you're like, resources.

00:35:17.240 --> 00:35:20.060
And you're like, Amazon, baby.

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:22.580
Or like, go to your
local fishmonger.

00:35:22.580 --> 00:35:23.830
I'm like, I've never been to--

00:35:23.830 --> 00:35:25.740
I've been cooking
for a long time,

00:35:25.740 --> 00:35:27.927
I don't know any fishmongers.

00:35:27.927 --> 00:35:29.510
SPEAKER: We can
introduce you to some.

00:35:29.510 --> 00:35:31.040
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Do they
wear like, rubber boots

00:35:31.040 --> 00:35:31.670
all the time?

00:35:31.670 --> 00:35:33.391
Where do you get them?

00:35:33.391 --> 00:35:35.390
I know California's better
than everywhere else,

00:35:35.390 --> 00:35:38.910
but we don't have that,
really, on the East Coast.

00:35:38.910 --> 00:35:43.490
So where you can get it, we've
got a really good spice guy

00:35:43.490 --> 00:35:45.420
in New York.

00:35:45.420 --> 00:35:47.840
His name is Leyora
[INAUDIBLE] and he's

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:50.660
got a spice shop
called La Boda Piece.

00:35:50.660 --> 00:35:54.080
And he makes the
best blends ever.

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:57.830
It is much easier now
to get those ingredients

00:35:57.830 --> 00:36:00.089
and those certain items.

00:36:00.089 --> 00:36:02.630
And it's, obviously, much easier
to get them shipped directly

00:36:02.630 --> 00:36:04.202
to you.

00:36:04.202 --> 00:36:04.910
But I don't know.

00:36:04.910 --> 00:36:06.493
I like going to
different supermarkets

00:36:06.493 --> 00:36:09.660
and ethnic supermarkets and
just tooling around and running

00:36:09.660 --> 00:36:10.160
around.

00:36:10.160 --> 00:36:12.920
And when we opened Zahav, we
had access to none of them.

00:36:12.920 --> 00:36:16.940
So it was like anytime my family
would visit, I was like, hey.

00:36:16.940 --> 00:36:22.460
Meet this guy on a corner,
he's going to give you a bag.

00:36:22.460 --> 00:36:24.170
Don't ask any questions.

00:36:24.170 --> 00:36:26.330
And then they'd get to the
States and they're like,

00:36:26.330 --> 00:36:29.180
all of my underwear smells
like Yemenite soup spice.

00:36:29.180 --> 00:36:30.950
Thank you very much.

00:36:30.950 --> 00:36:33.260
So it's a little bit easier now.

00:36:33.260 --> 00:36:34.940
But I don't know,
spices are really--

00:36:34.940 --> 00:36:38.090
it's funny because now,
just now, we have access

00:36:38.090 --> 00:36:40.100
to really good spices.

00:36:40.100 --> 00:36:42.980
Before, it was
like baharat, which

00:36:42.980 --> 00:36:46.790
is funny, too, because baharat
and hawaj, and curry, those all

00:36:46.790 --> 00:36:47.400
mean the same.

00:36:47.400 --> 00:36:50.840
They're all blends and there's
like, 17 different kinds.

00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:53.150
But I think now, people are
starting to understand it,

00:36:53.150 --> 00:36:57.560
and it's a very good way
to take local ingredients

00:36:57.560 --> 00:37:03.290
and really articulate
something that is very pure.

00:37:03.290 --> 00:37:06.980
What is the-- there's
one dish that we do.

00:37:06.980 --> 00:37:11.050
Oh, so we take figs right now.

00:37:11.050 --> 00:37:13.030
We have local figs
that are awesome.

00:37:13.030 --> 00:37:16.990
And we're barbecuing
them on charcoal

00:37:16.990 --> 00:37:18.790
and we're taking
Bulgarian feta cheese

00:37:18.790 --> 00:37:21.580
and whipping it with
[INAUDIBLE] and spooning it

00:37:21.580 --> 00:37:22.990
on top of the figs.

00:37:22.990 --> 00:37:26.500
And we're frying lentils
on top for crunch,

00:37:26.500 --> 00:37:29.110
and then we're taking
sumac from New Jersey--

00:37:29.110 --> 00:37:31.930
not poisonous-- and
we're blooming it

00:37:31.930 --> 00:37:34.030
and olive oil from Turkey.

00:37:34.030 --> 00:37:36.010
And we're pouring
on top of the feta

00:37:36.010 --> 00:37:39.220
to break it, because
any sauce needs to be

00:37:39.220 --> 00:37:40.720
broken with tons of olive oil.

00:37:40.720 --> 00:37:42.150
That's our rule.

00:37:42.150 --> 00:37:43.930
And it's nothing that
you've ever really

00:37:43.930 --> 00:37:47.050
had over their, or at
home, but the feeling

00:37:47.050 --> 00:37:49.300
is something that is super pure.

00:37:49.300 --> 00:37:52.270
So yeah, I would try [INAUDIBLE]
Kalustyan's, is, I think,

00:37:52.270 --> 00:37:55.870
is pretty good as well.

00:37:55.870 --> 00:37:59.380
And yeah.

00:37:59.380 --> 00:38:00.238
SPEAKER: Amazon.

00:38:00.238 --> 00:38:01.321
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Amazon.

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:06.150
You're asking an
impossible question,

00:38:06.150 --> 00:38:08.880
which is how to make your
tomatoes taste better.

00:38:08.880 --> 00:38:10.710
I mean, I feel like
in California, they're

00:38:10.710 --> 00:38:11.820
pretty awesome.

00:38:14.500 --> 00:38:18.360
So whenever we're in
Israel, I'm like, wow.

00:38:18.360 --> 00:38:20.490
Why does everything here
taste so much better?

00:38:20.490 --> 00:38:23.100
From a trade perspective, Israel
is, essentially, an island.

00:38:23.100 --> 00:38:28.260
So not even to be cool, but
everybody eats local there,

00:38:28.260 --> 00:38:30.330
and I think that
really helps out a lot.

00:38:30.330 --> 00:38:31.950
On the East Coast,
we have to deal

00:38:31.950 --> 00:38:37.050
with shipping from South
America or California, at best.

00:38:37.050 --> 00:38:40.140
And we have a small
window in the summer,

00:38:40.140 --> 00:38:43.965
actually, Jersey goes till
mid-October and they're great.

00:38:43.965 --> 00:38:47.060
So to make tomatoes
really concentrated,

00:38:47.060 --> 00:38:52.470
you gotta find the
tomatomonger, and just try

00:38:52.470 --> 00:38:54.450
to develop good
relationships with farms

00:38:54.450 --> 00:38:57.000
and go to farmer's markets,
I think would be it.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:58.910
We like to dehydrate a lot.

00:38:58.910 --> 00:39:03.870
So towards the
end of the season,

00:39:03.870 --> 00:39:07.740
we'll buy many cases of tomatoes
and we'll salt and preserve

00:39:07.740 --> 00:39:10.320
them and dry them a little
bit, and that kind of helps us.

00:39:10.320 --> 00:39:13.140
But yeah, it's a tricky thing.

00:39:13.140 --> 00:39:15.630
You have to elaborate.

00:39:15.630 --> 00:39:17.900
There is tomato powder--

00:39:17.900 --> 00:39:21.020
dried tomatoes,
entirely dry, ground.

00:39:21.020 --> 00:39:23.180
Adding a little bit of
tomato powder, sumac,

00:39:23.180 --> 00:39:27.490
and salt to fresh tomatoes
really wakes them up.

00:39:27.490 --> 00:39:28.580
SPEAKER: I love that idea.

00:39:28.580 --> 00:39:29.694
Yeah?

00:39:29.694 --> 00:39:31.712
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
Quick question for you.

00:39:31.712 --> 00:39:32.920
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Nailed it.

00:39:32.920 --> 00:39:34.760
Yeah.

00:39:34.760 --> 00:39:35.630
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:39:35.630 --> 00:39:37.790
How do you guys design
eating experiences

00:39:37.790 --> 00:39:38.680
at your restaurants?

00:39:38.680 --> 00:39:41.570
STEVEN COOK: I mean, I think
that was in addition to being

00:39:41.570 --> 00:39:43.946
an early American
restaurant that

00:39:43.946 --> 00:39:45.320
was calling itself
Israeli, which

00:39:45.320 --> 00:39:47.240
was a big thing 10 years ago.

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:49.820
I think the style of eating
kind of defines Zahav

00:39:49.820 --> 00:39:50.840
more than anything else.

00:39:50.840 --> 00:39:55.040
And when we worked
together at Marigold,

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:57.895
we had very few customers,
so we had a lot of time.

00:39:57.895 --> 00:40:00.020
We had a lot of time to
just sit on the back steps,

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:01.700
waiting for people
to come in and talk.

00:40:01.700 --> 00:40:05.060
And that was really
when Mike was started--

00:40:05.060 --> 00:40:07.700
we started we start having
this conversation of here's

00:40:07.700 --> 00:40:08.870
how they eat in Israel.

00:40:08.870 --> 00:40:10.190
You come in, sit down.

00:40:10.190 --> 00:40:13.870
Before you order any food,
a lot of food shows up.

00:40:13.870 --> 00:40:16.220
It's all the
salads, representing

00:40:16.220 --> 00:40:17.570
all the different cultures.

00:40:17.570 --> 00:40:20.330
And it's fresh bread
and it's hummus,

00:40:20.330 --> 00:40:21.890
and it's just the
sense of abundance

00:40:21.890 --> 00:40:24.800
that is really free of
anxiety of having to make

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:26.300
any choices at that point.

00:40:26.300 --> 00:40:28.460
And I think that's
kind of what we wanted

00:40:28.460 --> 00:40:33.020
to capture when we opened
Zahav because it was not

00:40:33.020 --> 00:40:33.780
American dining.

00:40:33.780 --> 00:40:35.180
It was nothing like that.

00:40:35.180 --> 00:40:39.260
And we were starting to see
Spanish tapas places open

00:40:39.260 --> 00:40:40.804
and do very well.

00:40:40.804 --> 00:40:41.720
That was 10 years ago.

00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:44.240
That was like the big
restaurant openings

00:40:44.240 --> 00:40:46.910
for these giant Spanish tapas
places that we all wanted--

00:40:46.910 --> 00:40:49.810
we were all jealous of because
they were just killing it.

00:40:49.810 --> 00:40:52.820
And as Mike says,
meze predates tapas

00:40:52.820 --> 00:40:54.420
by a couple of thousand years.

00:40:54.420 --> 00:40:57.366
So that sort of primed
the dining public

00:40:57.366 --> 00:40:58.490
to be able to eat that way.

00:40:58.490 --> 00:41:02.840
But yeah, when you come
into Zahav, basically,

00:41:02.840 --> 00:41:05.630
I mean, I would say
90% of the people

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:10.040
choose one of our options where
the menus kind of prescribe--

00:41:10.040 --> 00:41:14.060
you get some choices,
but you sit down.

00:41:14.060 --> 00:41:16.970
All these salads come to
the table, fresh laffa

00:41:16.970 --> 00:41:22.010
that Mike cooks, hummus, and
then you get a bunch of meze

00:41:22.010 --> 00:41:23.077
and a bunch of--

00:41:23.077 --> 00:41:24.660
excuse me-- a bunch
of grilled things.

00:41:24.660 --> 00:41:27.860
So it's super casual.

00:41:27.860 --> 00:41:29.360
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Everybody shares.

00:41:29.360 --> 00:41:30.770
Everybody rolls
up their sleeves.

00:41:30.770 --> 00:41:32.870
Everybody rips bread apart.

00:41:32.870 --> 00:41:34.109
And it's not formal.

00:41:34.109 --> 00:41:35.900
STEVEN COOK: We're
really proud of the fact

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:39.750
that the critic of
record in Philadelphia,

00:41:39.750 --> 00:41:42.170
instead of handing out
stars, he hands out bells.

00:41:42.170 --> 00:41:43.730
And you can get
four bells, and I

00:41:43.730 --> 00:41:46.197
think there's five or six four
bell restaurants in Philly,

00:41:46.197 --> 00:41:47.780
which we're really
proud to be one of.

00:41:47.780 --> 00:41:49.970
And I think our
price point and check

00:41:49.970 --> 00:41:53.610
average is probably about
half of the next cheapest one.

00:41:53.610 --> 00:41:59.990
And so, really, we try to
be hospitable and warm and

00:41:59.990 --> 00:42:01.327
approachable as much as we can.

00:42:01.327 --> 00:42:02.660
And part of that is price point.

00:42:02.660 --> 00:42:04.670
Part of that is
taking away anxiety

00:42:04.670 --> 00:42:07.620
from people when they come
to a restaurant with a menu

00:42:07.620 --> 00:42:11.460
that they might not know
what the words mean.

00:42:11.460 --> 00:42:14.174
So that's a huge part
of success, I think.

00:42:14.174 --> 00:42:16.340
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Zahav
is, essentially, our house.

00:42:16.340 --> 00:42:22.190
I mean, that's hospitality
on every level is that.

00:42:22.190 --> 00:42:27.050
Eating with my family in
Israel is, essentially,

00:42:27.050 --> 00:42:30.110
being force fed
way too much food,

00:42:30.110 --> 00:42:32.900
but really being made
to feel comfortable.

00:42:32.900 --> 00:42:37.160
And that's what we try
to do with every guest.

00:42:37.160 --> 00:42:40.460
SPEAKER: So if that's your
launch point in your home base,

00:42:40.460 --> 00:42:43.910
how did you start deciding what
other types of restaurants you

00:42:43.910 --> 00:42:45.560
might want to have?

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:48.670
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Well, we opened

00:42:48.670 --> 00:42:50.720
Zahar in 2008, which
was not a great year

00:42:50.720 --> 00:42:54.890
to open any small business, let
alone an Israeli restaurant.

00:42:54.890 --> 00:42:57.560
And the Phillies had
won the World Series

00:42:57.560 --> 00:42:59.990
that year, which
is great if you own

00:42:59.990 --> 00:43:03.440
a bar with a television
in it, not a restaurant.

00:43:03.440 --> 00:43:05.030
So we were a super slow.

00:43:05.030 --> 00:43:07.940
We'd opened another
restaurant that was doing OK.

00:43:07.940 --> 00:43:10.040
And we were hanging
out with our friends

00:43:10.040 --> 00:43:13.070
that were the first people to
bring fancy coffee to Philly.

00:43:13.070 --> 00:43:16.080
And we they wanted
to open a donut shop.

00:43:16.080 --> 00:43:17.580
They wanted to do
coffee and donuts.

00:43:17.580 --> 00:43:20.450
We were eating tons of Korean
fried chicken at the time.

00:43:20.450 --> 00:43:24.170
So we were like, why don't we
do donuts, coffee and chicken?

00:43:24.170 --> 00:43:25.490
We're not doing anything else.

00:43:25.490 --> 00:43:27.110
Our restaurants
are kind of slow.

00:43:27.110 --> 00:43:29.630
We each put a couple thousand
dollars-- five partners

00:43:29.630 --> 00:43:32.030
put a couple thousand
dollars in a pot

00:43:32.030 --> 00:43:34.910
and we opened Federal Donuts,
which serves donuts, coffee,

00:43:34.910 --> 00:43:35.720
and fried chicken.

00:43:35.720 --> 00:43:37.460
SPEAKER: Just because you felt
like eating donuts and coffee

00:43:37.460 --> 00:43:38.210
and fried chicken.

00:43:38.210 --> 00:43:38.840
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
We were bored.

00:43:38.840 --> 00:43:40.756
SPEAKER: This is my kind
of business decision.

00:43:40.756 --> 00:43:41.450
I like it.

00:43:41.450 --> 00:43:43.200
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: If
we each lose $5,000,

00:43:43.200 --> 00:43:45.230
it would totally
be the worst thing.

00:43:45.230 --> 00:43:46.550
Let's just try it out.

00:43:46.550 --> 00:43:48.170
And then on day two,
we're like, wow,

00:43:48.170 --> 00:43:51.710
this is the best idea
we've ever had in our life.

00:43:51.710 --> 00:43:54.484
And that was what,
five years ago?

00:43:54.484 --> 00:43:56.150
STEVEN COOK: No, that
was six years ago.

00:43:56.150 --> 00:43:56.880
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Six years ago,

00:43:56.880 --> 00:43:58.700
and now we have
five or six of them.

00:43:58.700 --> 00:44:03.480
And super random, but delicious.

00:44:03.480 --> 00:44:06.709
And it's like the
three major food

00:44:06.709 --> 00:44:07.875
groups in the United States.

00:44:11.469 --> 00:44:12.510
We've owned a restaurant.

00:44:12.510 --> 00:44:15.960
So that's sort of an outlier.

00:44:15.960 --> 00:44:18.990
But we had a barbecue
restaurant at one point.

00:44:18.990 --> 00:44:21.210
We had a Mexican
restaurant at one point.

00:44:21.210 --> 00:44:26.130
The food that we serve
at all of our restaurants

00:44:26.130 --> 00:44:28.890
are the things that
are very personal to us

00:44:28.890 --> 00:44:30.700
and we have this
emotional connection.

00:44:30.700 --> 00:44:35.250
And as I said, things go wrong
all the time in restaurants.

00:44:35.250 --> 00:44:40.230
And you feel you have this
like obligation a little bit

00:44:40.230 --> 00:44:42.690
to your heritage to
really keep things alive.

00:44:42.690 --> 00:44:44.582
It helps.

00:44:44.582 --> 00:44:47.040
We've got a couple really cool
projects that are definitely

00:44:47.040 --> 00:44:52.789
related to Israel.

00:44:52.789 --> 00:44:54.330
We've got a couple
really cool things

00:44:54.330 --> 00:44:56.038
happening in the next
year that we're not

00:44:56.038 --> 00:44:57.090
quite ready to announce.

00:44:57.090 --> 00:45:00.997
But you guys should definitely
take a field trip to Philly.

00:45:00.997 --> 00:45:01.830
SPEAKER: Hear, hear.

00:45:01.830 --> 00:45:05.910
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: It's
only a five hour flight.

00:45:05.910 --> 00:45:07.650
But the cost of doing
anything in Philly

00:45:07.650 --> 00:45:10.620
is so much cheaper than the
Bay Area, so it's nothing.

00:45:10.620 --> 00:45:12.120
Going to a convenience
store for you

00:45:12.120 --> 00:45:15.180
is spending a
weekend in our city.

00:45:15.180 --> 00:45:18.300
SPEAKER: Our team is working
on some delicious bites,

00:45:18.300 --> 00:45:20.780
and we hope you guys will
stick around and sign some cook

00:45:20.780 --> 00:45:21.480
books for those lucky few.

00:45:21.480 --> 00:45:22.855
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Yeah, we will.

00:45:22.855 --> 00:45:24.170
Thanks so much for having us.

00:45:24.170 --> 00:45:25.320
SPEAKER: Well then,
please, join me.

00:45:25.320 --> 00:45:26.162
Thank you so much.

00:45:26.162 --> 00:45:27.620
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Yeah, thank you.

00:45:27.620 --> 00:45:28.220
Thank you.

00:45:28.220 --> 00:45:31.270
[APPLAUSE]

